(133, 133, NULL, 'query selects non-template extension elements.', 'Scenario: Let''s say I have a template ''atomic'' and a set of 2 plugins (authentication/atomic, user/atomic).\r<br>Going to ``Extensions > Template Manager > Styles`` shows up 2 additional styles for ''atomic'' template (which in fact are plugins with same name).\r<br>\r<br>this appeared after migration 1.7 > 2.5 probably due to restructured query\r<br>\r<br>duplicate of #93', 3, 0, 10, '2012-02-21 14:28:53', '2012-02-21 14:31:04', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'https://github.com/joomla/joomla-cms/pull/133.diff', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(134, 134, NULL, 'The constants IS_WIN, IS_MAC, IS_UNIX are used in the system?', 'Checking the file [libraries/import.php](https://github.com/joomla/joomla-cms/blob/master/libraries/import.php#L22)  I''m  a question regarding the use of constants **IS_WIN**, **IS_MAC**, **IS_UNIX**.\r<br>\r<br>Somewhere in the CMS are used?\r<br>\r<br>Moreover [libraries/joomla/filesystem/path.php](https://github.com/joomla/joomla-cms/blob/master/libraries/joomla/filesystem/path.php#L13)  file defines constants: JPATH_ISWIN and JPATH_ISMAC on lines 13, 16 respectively.\r<br>\r<br>The file [./libraries/joomla/application/application.php](https://github.com/joomla/joomla-cms/blob/master//libraries/joomla/application/application.php#L1184) define function ''isWinOS''\r<br>\r<br>\r<br>The object **JFTP** [in its constructor](https://github.com/joomla/joomla-cms/blob/master/libraries/joomla/client/ftp.php#L157) sets the variable **OS**.\r<br>\r<br>All these files make use of the form:\r<br>\r<br>```php\r<br><?php\r<br>substr(PHP_OS, 0, 3)\r<br>\r<br>```\r<br>to determine the operating system.\r<br>\r<br>the external libraries for example:  **phpmailer** and **geshi** also make use of this form.\r<br>\r<br>IMHO is necessary to define these variables.\r<br>\r<br>However appear in the documentation. <https://github.com/joomla/joomla-platform/blob/staging/docs/manual/en-US/chapters/introduction.xml#L41>\r<br>\r<br>Personally I consider that:\r<br>\r<br>1. - These constants should not exist.\r<br>\r<br>2. - Or if the file ''iasf.php'' is loaded before the other files, then you should make use of these constants.\r<br>\r<br>\r<br>Personally I think it''s the first best solution(educes the learning curve of the framework).\r<br>\r<br>P. S. I would like to help review this detail.', 3, 0, 1, '2012-02-22 06:34:50', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
